  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      To determine the relationship between degree of sodium restriction and dietary compliance
      with clinical outcome of diuresis of portal hypertensive ascites in cirrhotic patients from a
      county hospital population.

      Primary objective: Demonstrate that, when accompanied by the appropriate diuretic regimen, a
      No Added Salt diet (4 grams sodium per day) is as effective as a Low Sodium diet (2 grams
      sodium per day) in the management of cirrhotic ascites.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Secondary objectives:

        1. Demonstrate that patient acceptance is greater and diuresis faster with a No Added Salt
           diet compared with a Low Sodium diet

        2. Demonstrate that side-effects of diuretic therapy are the same or less when patients are
           on a No Added Salt diet

        3. Determine if glomerular filtration rate estimated from the modified diet in renal
           disease equation differs from that obtained by a 24 hour urinary creatinine in patients
           with cirrhotic ascites
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
